iness Research, Vol. 5 Iss 2 pp.&nbsp;190 \u2013 213]\n\n== External links ==\n* Nadia Mustafa, [http://www.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1016266,00.html?promoid=rss_top \"What About Gross National Happiness?\"], [[Time (magazine)|Time]], 10 January 2005\n* [[Rajni Bakshi]], [http://www.alternet.org/envirohealth/21083/ \"Gross National Happiness\"], ''Resurgence'', 25 January 2005\n* International Institute of Management \u2013 US based GHN research, [http://www.iim-edu.org/grossnationalhappiness/ GNH policy white paper]\n* Bhutan 2008 [https://web.archive.org/web/20081121215814/http://2008.bhutan-360.com/2007/11/25/gross-national-happiness/ Paeans to the King]\n* [http://www.earth.columbia.edu/sitefiles/file/Sachs%20Writing/2012/World%20Happiness%20Report.pdf World Happiness Report]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2jf9xrnUjpI Bhutan, Gross National Happiness and Sustainable Development \u2013 YouTube] (12:31)\n* [http://www.gnhusa.org Gross National Happiness USA] United States-based non-profit using GNH framing to spark dialogue and inform public policy.\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{Global economic classifications}}\n{{Bhutanese society}}\n\n[[Category:Macroeconomic indicators]]\n[[Category:Ecological economics]]\n[[Category:Environmental economics]]\n[[Category:Economic ideologies]]\n[[Category:Economy of Bhutan]]\n[[Category:Applied ethics]]\n[[Category:Happiness indices]]\n", "name_user": "AquariRajan282011", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSpread of GNH Outside of Bhutan", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gross_National_Happiness"}
{"title_page": "IS-1 and IS-2", "text_new": "{{For|the predecessor to the IS-2 in the tank series|Kliment Voroshilov tank}}\n{{redirect-distinguish|IS2|ISIS (disambiguation){{!}}ISIS|ISS (disambiguation){{!}}ISS|i2s}}\n{{short description|Soviet WWII heavy tank}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name = IS-2\n|image = [[File:IS-2 Model 1943 - Sevastopol.png|300px]]\n|caption = IS-2 Model 1943, in [[Sevastopol]].\n|type = [[Heavy tank]]\n| origin             = [[Soviet Union]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = Yes\n| is_artillery       = Yes\n| is_vehicle         = Yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n|wars = {{plainlist|\n* [[World War II]]\n* [[Korean War]]}}\n|designer = [[Zhozef Kotin]]<br />[[Nikolay Dukhov]]\n|number = {{plainlist|\n* 3,854}}\n|spec_label = IS-2 Model 1944<ref>Zaloga 1984, p 176.</ref>\n|length = {{convert|9.90|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|width = {{convert|3.09|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|height = {{convert|2.73|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|used_by = {{plainlist|\n* [[Soviet Union]]\n* [[China]]\n* [[Cuba]]\n* [[Czechoslovakia]]\n* [[DPRK]]}}\n|design_date = {{plainlist|\n* 1943}}\n|manufacturer = [[Kirov Factory]], [[UZTM]]\n|unit_cost = IS-2 Model 1944: 264,400 rubles<ref name=\"tank\">{{cite web|url=http://tank.uw.ru/archive/sebestoimostx/|website=tank.uw.ru|title=\u0421\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u0445 \u0442\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430\u043c|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n|production_date = {{plainlist|\n* 1943\u201345}}\n|variants =\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight = {{convert|46|t|ST LT|lk=out}}\n|crew = 4\n<!-- Artillery specifications -->\n|elevation =\n|traverse =\n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n|armour = '''IS-2 Model 1944:'''<br />Hull front: 100&nbsp;mm at 60\u00b0 angle<br />Lower glacis: 100&nbsp;mm at 30\u00b0 angle<br />Turret front: 100 mm (rounded)<br />Mantlet: 155 mm (rounded)<br />Hull side: 90\u2013130 mm at 9-25\u00b0<br />Turret side: 90 mm at 20\u00b0 angle.\n|primary_armament = [[122 mm gun M1931/37 (A-19)|D25-T]] 122 mm gun (28 rounds)\n|secondary_armament = 1\u00d7[[DShK]], 3\u00d7[[Degtyarev light machine gun|DT]] (2,079 rounds)\n|engine = 12-cyl. diesel [[Kharkiv model V-2|model V-2]]\n|engine_power = 600 hp (450 kW)\n|pw_ratio = 13 hp/tonne\n|transmission =\n|suspension = [[torsion bar]]\n|clearance =\n|fuel_capacity = {{convert|820|l|abbr=on}}\n|vehicle_range = {{convert|240|km|abbr=on}}\n|speed = {{convert|37|km/h|abbr=on}}\n}}\n{{Cold War tanks}}\nThe '''IS-1''', redesignated the '''IS-2''' for security reasons, is the first [[Soviet]] [[heavy tank]] model of the [[IS tank series]].  It saw combat in [[World War II]] as well as service in other Soviet allied countries after the war.\n\n==Design and production==\n=== Object 237 KV-85 and IS-85/IS-1 ===\n{{anchor |Object 237|IS-85|IS-1}}\n[[File:KV-85 right side view.JPG|left|thumb|The KV-85 was a stop-gap solution until the introduction of the IS series. Note the modified [[Kliment Voroshilov tank|KV]] chassis with the removal of the hull machine-gunner/radio operator's station with one operated by the driver, and the driver's station slightly centered at the front; a staple design of all IS-series tank.]]\n[[File:IS 1 prototyp.jpg|thumbnail|IS-85 (IS-1) Prototype equipped with [[85 mm air defense gun M1939 (52-K)|D-5T]] gun. Later IS-2 converted models were replaced with the [[122 mm gun M1931/37 (A-19)|122mm D-25T gun]] whilst retaining the same hull.]]\nThe [[Kliment Voroshilov tank|KV-1]] was criticized by its crews for its poor mobility and the lack of a larger caliber gun than the [[T-34]] medium tank. It was much more expensive than the T-34, without having greater combat performance. Moscow ordered some KV-1 assembly lines to shift to T-34 production, leading to fears that KV-1 production would be halted and the SKB-2 design bureau, led by Kotin, closed.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1994|p=4}} In 1942, this problem was partially addressed by the KV-1S tank, which had thinner armor than the original, making it lighter and faster. It was competitive with the T-34 but at the cost of no longer having the heavier armor. Production of the KV-1S was gradually replaced by the [[SU-152]]{{Sfn|Zaloga|1996|p=44}} and ended in April 1943.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1996|p=42}}\n\nThe capture of a German [[Tiger I|Tiger]] tank in January 1943 led to a decision to develop a new heavy tank, which was given the codename Object 237.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1994|p=5}} Before Object 237 had time to mature, intense tank fighting in the summer of 1943 demanded a response. Dukhov's team was instructed to create a [[wikt:stopgap#Pronunciation|stopgap]] KV tank, the KV-85, which was armed with the [[85 mm air defense gun M1939 (52-K)|52-K]]-derivative gun of the [[SU-85]], the 85&nbsp;mm D-5T, that proved capable of penetrating the [[Tiger I]] from {{convert|1000|m|yd|abbr=on}}. The KV-85 was created by mounting an Object 237 turret on a KV-1S hull. To accommodate the Object 237 turret, the KV-1S hull was modified, increasing the diameter of the turret ring with fillets on the sides of the hull. The radio operator was replaced with an ammunition rack for the larger 85&nbsp;mm ammunition. The hull MG was then moved to the opposite side of the driver and fixed in place to be operated by the driver. From September to October 1943, a total of 130 KV-85s were produced, before the assembly lines began to shift over. Like the KV-1S, the KV-85 served in dwindling numbers and was quickly overshadowed by the superior IS series.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1996|p=45}}\n\nThe Object 237 prototype, a version of the cancelled [[KV-13]], was accepted for production as the '''IS-85''' heavy tank.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1994|p=6}} First deliveries were made in October 1943, and the tanks went immediately into service. Production ended in January 1944. Its designation was simplified to IS-1 after the introduction of the IS-122, later renamed as IS-2 for security purposes.\n\n===Object 240 IS-2===\n==== Gun ====\nBy 1943, engineers had succeeded in mounting the 85&nbsp;mm gun to the T-34 medium tank, making it as well-armed as the KV-85 heavy tank. Efforts to up-gun the IS-85 began in late 1943. Two candidate weapons were the D-25 122&nbsp;mm tank gun, the ballistic characteristics of which were identical to the [[122 mm gun M1931/37 (A-19)|A-19 122&nbsp;mm gun]],<ref name=Testing/> and the [[D-10 tank gun|D-10 100&nbsp;mm gun]], which was based on a naval [[dual-purpose gun]]. The D-10 had been designed for anti-tank fire and had better armor penetration than the A-19, but the smaller caliber meant it had a less useful [[High explosives|high explosive]] round. Also, the D-10 was a relatively new weapon in short supply, while there was excess production capacity for the A-19 and its ammunition. Compared to the older [[F-34 tank gun|F-34 76.2&nbsp;mm]] tank gun, the D-25 delivered 5.37 times the muzzle energy.\n\nAfter testing both the D-25 and D-10 on the IS-122, the former was selected as the main armament of the new tank. The D-25 used a separate shell and powder charge, resulting in a lower rate of fire compared to the single-piece ammunition used in most tanks, a serious disadvantage in tank-to-tank engagements. Soviet proving-ground tests showed that the D-25 could penetrate the front armor of the German [[Panther tank|Panther]] at {{convert|2500|m|yd|abbr=on}} while the D-10 could do so at a maximum range of {{convert|1500|m|yd|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Testing>{{cite web|title=Report on the results of testing of the 100 mm and the 122 mm tank guns at the Kubinka proving grounds|url=http://english.battlefield.ru/documents/29-technics/96-testing-100-mm-and-122-mm-tank-guns.html|website=The Russian Battlefield|accessdate=27 October 2014 |date=September 12, 1944 |last1=Tolochkov |last2=Volosatov}}</ref><ref>Zaloga 1984:172</ref> It was therefore considered an adequate anti-tank gun. First deliveries of IS-122s mounted with this gun were in December of 1943.<ref name=IS1+2 />\n\n[[File:D25T shells.svg|left|thumb|Projectiles and charges of the separate-loading ammunition of the A-19/D-25T 122mm gun. Left to right: cartridge case, high-explosive/fragmentation shell OF-471, armor-piercing high explosive shell BR-471, armor-piercing ballistic capped shell BR-471B. All shells are shown from two sides.]]\n\nA Wa Pruef 1 Report dated 5 October 1944 has data on the penetration ranges of the 122&nbsp;mm A-19 gun against a Panther tank angled at 30 degrees; this estimated that the A-19 gun was unable to penetrate the upper glacis plate of the Panther from any distance, could penetrate the lower glacis plate from {{convert|100|m|yd|abbr=on}}, could penetrate the mantlet from {{convert|500|m|yd|abbr=on}} and could penetrate the front turret from {{convert|1500|m|yd|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Panther128>{{cite book|last1=Jentz|first1=Thomas|title=Germany's Panther Tank: The Quest for Combat Supremacy|date=1995|publisher=Schiffer Military History|isbn=0887408125|page=128}}</ref> The Panther's {{convert|40|\u2013|50|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick side armor would have been exposed and vulnerable at such an angle; the sides at 30 degrees were penetrable from over {{convert|3500|m|yd|abbr=on}} according to the same Wa Pruef 1 report.<ref name=Panther128/> Testing with captured [[Tiger II|Tiger Ausf Bs]] in [[Kubinka]] showed that the 122&nbsp;mm D-25T was capable of penetrating the [[Tiger II|Tiger Ausf B's]] turret from {{convert|1000|\u2013|1500|m|yd|abbr=on}} and the weld joint or edges of the front hull plates at ranges of {{convert|500|\u2013|600|m|yd|abbr=on}}.<ref name=WasTheTigerReallyKing>{{cite web |url=http://english.battlefield.ru/analytics/126-was-the-tiger-really-king.html |title=Was the Tiger really King?|work=The Russian Battlefield|accessdate= 24 October 2014}}</ref> In 1944, the BR-471 was the sole armor-piercing round available. An improved version, the BR-471B ({{lang-ru|\u0411\u0420-471\u0411|links=no}}) was developed in spring 1945, but was available in quantity only after World War II ended.<ref>David R. Higgins, \"King Tiger vs IS-2: Operation Solstice 1945\", p. 29</ref>\n\nAccording to the same Wa Pruef 1 report, it was estimated that at 30 degree obliquity the hull armor of the Soviet [[IS-2]] model 1943 would be defeated by [[Tiger I]] between {{convert|100|and|300|m|mi|abbr=on}} at the driver's front plate and nose,{{sfn|Jentz|Doyle|1993|pp=19\u201320}} while the IS-2's 122&nbsp;mm gun would penetrate the Tiger's front armor from between {{convert|500|and|1500|m|mi|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Jentz|Doyle|1993|pp=19\u201320}} A Panther had to close to {{convert|600|m|yards|abbr=on}} to guarantee penetration of the IS-2's frontal armor (The Panther's 75&nbsp;mm gun could penetrate the IS-2 model 1943's mantlet from {{convert|400|m|yards|abbr=on}}, front turret from {{convert|800|m|yards|abbr=on}}, and driver's front plate from {{convert|600|m|yards|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Jentz 1995 p. 128\">Jentz 1995, p. 128</ref>), while the IS-2 could penetrate the Panther at ranges of {{convert|1000|m|yards|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref group=Notes>The German military intelligence journal for tank crews \"Nachrichtenblatt der Panzertruppen Nr.12, June 1944 p. 34\" reported that the IS-2 could be successful attacked at approximately {{convert|500|m|yd|abbr=on}} at the angle of 30 degrees. This calculation was derived from firing tables \"Pz. Beschusstafel\" created against the KV-85. Steven Zaloga makes therefore an unfavorable comparison (30\u00b0 to 90\u00b0 for the range of destruction) for the Panther over its adversary</ref> However, in the summer of 1944, the Germans experienced a shortage of manganese and had to switch to using high-carbon steel alloyed with nickel, which made armor very brittle, especially at the seam welds. The performance of the 122&nbsp;mm AP shells of the IS-2 against the Panther improved considerably. The reports from the front described cases where the BR-471 APHE round 122&nbsp;mm projectile fired from {{convert|2500|m|yd|abbr=on}} ricocheted off the front armor of a Panther, leaving huge breaches to it.<ref name=\"IS1+2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.battlefield.ru/js1-js2/stranitsa-3.html |title=IS-1 and IS-2 Heavy tanks |work=The Russian Battlefield|accessdate= 20 March 2017 |date=20 September 2005 |quote=source: Valery Potapov.}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=March 2017}} According to Steven Zaloga, the IS-2<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite book|last1=Zaloga|first1=Steven|title=IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944-73|date=1994|publisher=Osprey |page=12}}</ref> and Tiger I could knock each other out in normal combat distances below {{convert|1000|m|yd|abbr=on}}. At any range, the performance of each tank against each other was dependent on the crew and combat situation.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zaloga|first1=Steven|title=IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944\u201373|date=1994|publisher=Osprey |page=13}}</ref>\n\n[[File:IS-2 scheme.jpg|thumb|Line drawing of IS-2]]\nThe large 122&nbsp;mm [[High explosive|HE]] shell was its main asset, proving highly useful and destructive as an infantry-killer. In extremis, the IS-2 engaged enemy heavy armor with OF-471 ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u0424-471|links=no}}) high explosive projectiles. These shells had a mass of {{convert|25|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, a muzzle velocity of {{cvt|800|m/s|ft/s}}, and were equipped with a {{convert|3.8|kg|lb|abbr=on}} [[TNT]] charge. The explosive power could blow off an enemy tank turret, drive sprocket and tread off the heaviest German tank even if it could not penetrate the armor.<ref name=\"books.google.com.vn\"/><ref name=\"books.google.com.vn\"/><ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=The Encyclopedia of Weapons of World War II|author=Bishop, C.|date=2002|publisher=MetroBooks|isbn=9781586637620|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MuGsf0psjvcC&pg=PA41|page=41|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"google\"/> Mechanical shock and explosion was often enough to knock out enemy heavy tanks.<ref name=\"books.google.com.vn\">{{cite book|title=Soviet Heavy Tanks: World War 2 In Review Special|author=Merriam, R.|date=2016|publisher=Merriam Press|isbn=9781576385814|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RLjQDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA5|page=5|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe most recognizable disadvantage of the D-25T gun was its slow rate of fire due to the large size and weight of the shells; only one to one and a half rounds per minute could be fired, initially.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=D-25 Tank gun|url=http://www.battlefield.ru/d25.html|website=The Russian Battlfield|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> After some design improvements, including a semi-automatic drop breech over the previously manual screw breech, the rate of fire increased to 2\u20133 rounds per minute.<ref name=\"auto\"/> According to other sources, the increase may have amounted to 3\u20134 rounds per minute.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zaloga|first1=Steven|title=IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944-73|date=1994|publisher=Osprey Publishing Ltd.|isbn=9781849084055|page=41}}</ref> Another limitation imposed by the size of its ammunition in a relatively small vehicle was the ammunition stowage: only 28 rounds could be carried inside the tank, with a complement of 20 HE rounds and 8 AP rounds the norm.<ref>Zaloga 1984:175</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Higgins|first1=David|title=Kingtiger vs. IS-2|date=2011|publisher=Osprey |isbn=9781849084055 |page=74}}</ref>\n\n==== Production ====\nThe IS-122 prototype replaced the IS-85 and began mass production as the IS-2. The 85&nbsp;mm guns could be reserved for the new T-34-85 medium tank and some of the IS-1s built were rearmed before leaving the factory and issued as IS-2s. It was slightly lighter and faster than the heaviest KV model 1942 tank, with thicker front armor and a much-improved turret design. The tank could carry thicker armor than the KV series, while remaining lighter, due to the better layout of the armor envelope. The KV's armor was less well-shaped and featured heavy armor even on the rear, while the IS series concentrated its armor at the front. The IS-2 was slightly heavier than the Panther, much lighter than the [[Tiger I]] and [[Tiger II]] and had a lower silhouette than both. Western observers tended to criticize Soviet tanks for their lack of finish and crude construction. The Soviets argued that it was warranted, considering the need for wartime expediency and the typically short battlefield life of their tanks.<ref>Perrett 1987:20</ref>\n\n[[File:IS-2 scheme of armour.jpg|thumb|Armor plan of IS-2, models 1943 (top) and 1944 (bottom).]]\nEarly IS-2s can be identified by the 'stepped' front hull casting with its small, opening driver's visor. The early tanks lacked gun tube travel locks or anti-aircraft-capable machine guns and had narrow mantlets.\n\nIn late 1944, the stepped hull front was replaced with an improved single casting of 120&nbsp;mm thickness angled at 60 degrees. This new nose lacked the opening driver's visor. It is sometimes incorrectly referred to as the IS-2M, but that designation actually refers to a much later modernization program from the 1950s. Other minor upgrades included the addition of a travel lock on the hull rear, wider mantlet and, on very late models, an [[DShK|anti-aircraft machine gun]].\n\nIn comparison to the Tiger I, the IS-2 had modest advantages in armour, even though it was 10 tons lighter<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zaloga|first1=Steven|title=IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944\u201373|date=1994|publisher=Osprey |page=25}}</ref> In 1944, IS-2 tank was the only large-scale Allied tank whose armor provided some protection from the well-known Tiger 88mm long-barreled guns and Panther 75mm L/70 guns.\n\nIn the mid-1950s, the remaining IS-2 tanks (mostly model 1944 variants) were upgraded to the IS-2M standard, which introduced fittings such as external fuel tanks on the rear hull (the basic IS-2 had these only on the hull sides), stowage bins on both sides of the hull and protective skirting along the top edges of the [[Caterpillar track|tracks]].\n\n== Combat history ==\nThe IS-2 tank first saw combat in early 1944, equipping Guards Heavy Tank Regiments of the Red Army. First encountered by [[Otto Carius]] and a fellow Tiger I. After knocking out a column of T-34's, Carius moved into the nearby village of Malinava where he came face to face with the new IS-2. It was quickly destroyed, however as Carius moved further into the village he discovered a platoon of IS-2s dispatching of the group without a loss with the help of a second Tiger I. <ref>{{cite|title=Tigers in the Mud: The Combat Career of German Panzer Commander Otto Carius|first1=Otto|last1=Carius|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Tigers_in_the_Mud.htmlid=KdZZANBqbHMC&printsec=frontcover&source=kp_read_button&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=978-0425236895}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2020}}\nA regiment had 21 IS-2 tanks in four companies of five tanks each and one being used by the regimental commander.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1994|p=8}} The special tank regiments were reserved for important attacks, often to spearhead attempts to break through fortified German positions like anti-tank defence lines and bunkers.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1994|p=8}} The tanks supporting infantry in the assault by destroying bunkers, buildings, dug-in weapons and engaging German armoured vehicles. Once a breakthrough was achieved, lighter and more mobile tanks were used for exploitation and mopping-up. The IS-2 tank first saw action in [[Ukraine]] in early 1944 and claimed to have destroyed more than forty Tigers and [[Elefant]]s for the loss of only eight tanks. While the German heavy tanks could knock out the IS-2, they had no real answer to its {{nowrap|122 mm}} gun, which easily outgunned them.<ref>Tiger I and Tiger II. [[Anthony Tucker-Jones]]. Pen and Sword, 2013. {{ISBN|1473826780}}. P 160</ref>\n\n=== Ogl\u0119d\u00f3w ===\nOn the morning of 11 August 1944, the 16th Panzer Division attacked the 53d Guards Tank Brigade reinforced by the 71st Independent Guards Heavy Tank Regiment in the town of [[Ogl\u0119d\u00f3w]], toward Stasz\u00f3w. The extremely sandy terrain forced the eleven King Tigers to keep to the roads, whilst the defending Soviet forces positioned their tanks and assault guns in ambush positions and concentrated on the known German avenues of approach.<ref>Sledgehammers: Strengths and Flaws of Tiger Tank Battalions in World War II. Christopher W. Wilbeck. Aberjona, 2004. p.134</ref> When the attack started, three Tiger IIs were destroyed by fire from Soviet IS-2 tanks and one more Tiger II was knocked out a few hours later by a T-34/76 at a range of less than 400 meters. Later in the day, Soviet forces counter-attacked and seized the town of [[Ogl\u0119d\u00f3w]] and found three abandoned Tiger IIs. The capture of these tanks allowed the Soviets to conduct tests at Kubinka and to evaluate its strengths and weaknesses.<ref name=\"Sledgehammers 2004. p.135\">Sledgehammers: Strengths and Flaws of Tiger Tank Battalions in World War II. Christopher W. Wilbeck. Aberjona, 2004. p.135</ref>\n\nOver the next two days the Red Army advanced on Stasz\u00f3w and in several counter-attacks, Heavy Tank Battalion 501 lost seven more Tiger IIs. Virtually all of these were destroyed by Soviet tanks occupying a defensive position against those German attacks.<ref name=\"Sledgehammers 2004. p.135\"/> In three days of fighting, Soviet forces destroyed or captured 14 of 30 Tiger IIs to an approximately equal number of Soviet IS-2s and T-34s.<ref name=\"Sledgehammers 2004. p.135\"/><ref>{{cite|title=Hitler's Panzers: The Lightning Attacks that Revolutionized Warfare|first1=Dennis |last1=Showalter|publisher=Penguin|date=2009|page=315|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Mcx7PGEdSKAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Hitler%27s+Panzers:+The+Lightning+Attacks+that+Revolutionized+Warfare&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwia8KGgoO7XAhXmIMAKHaeNCxEQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=501st%20Heavy%20Tank%20battalion&f=false|isbn=978-0425236895}}</ref>\n\n\n=== Post World War II ===\nBy the 1950s, the emergence of the [[main battle tank]] concept\u2014combining medium-tank mobility with the firepower and armor of the heavy tank\u2014had rendered heavy tanks obsolete. In the late 1960s the remaining Soviet heavy tanks were transferred to Red Army reserve service and storage. The IS-2 Model 1944 remained in service much longer in the armies of [[Cuba]], [[China]] and [[North Korea]]. A regiment of Chinese IS-2s was available for use in the [[Korean War]] but saw no service there.\n\nAfter the Korean War, China attempted to reverse-engineer the IS-2/IS-3 as the Type 122 medium tank. The project was cancelled in favor of the [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]], a copy of the Soviet T-54A\n\n== Variants ==\n;KV-85: A stopgap model built from a modified KV-1S hull mated to an Object 237(IS-1)'s turret and armed with the 85&nbsp;mm D-5T.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zaloga|first1=Steven|title=IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944-1944|date=1994|publisher=Osprey Publishing Ltd.|isbn=1855323966|pages=5\u20136}}</ref>\n;IS-85 (IS-1): 1943 model armed with an 85&nbsp;mm gun. When IS-2 production started, many were re-gunned with 122&nbsp;mm guns before being issued.\n;IS-100: A prototype version armed with a 100&nbsp;mm gun; it went into trials against the ''IS-122'' which was armed with a 122&nbsp;mm gun. Though the IS-100 was reported to have better anti-armor capabilities, the latter was chosen due to better all-around performance.\n;IS-122 (IS-2 model 1943): 1943 model, armed with A-19 122&nbsp;mm gun.\n;IS-2 model 1944 (sometimes \"IS-2m\"):1944 improvement with D25-T 122&nbsp;mm gun, with faster-loading drop breech and new fire control, improved simpler hull front.\n;IS-2M: 1950s modernization of IS-2 tanks.\n\n==Operators==\n;{{Flag|China}}\n* [[People's Liberation Army]]: 60 IS-2s delivered in 1950\u20131951. Operated during the Korean War and in concrete bunkers along the Sino-Soviet border.\n;{{Flag|Cuba}}\n* [[Cuban Army]]: 41 IS-2Ms delivered in 1960.\n;{{Flag|Czechoslovakia}}\n* [[Czechoslovak Army]]: 8 IS-2/IS-2M in service between 1945-1960.\n;{{Flag|East Germany}}\n* [[National People's Army|NVA]]: 60 IS-2 delivered 1956. Operated until 1963.\n;{{Flag|Nazi Germany}}\n* [[Wehrmacht]]: Captured one or two IS-2 in May 1945.<ref>Das letzte Jahr der deutschen Heeres 1944-1945 \" von Wolfgang Fleischer / Podzun-Pallas Verlag</ref>\n;{{Flag|Hungary}}\n* [[Hungarian People's Army]]: 68 IS-2s in service between 1950-1956. After the crackdown of the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] all were returned to the Soviet Union.<ref>http://epa.oszk.hu/01600/01639/00008/pdf/EPA01639_elso_szazad_2012_tel_061-069.pdf</ref>\n;{{Flag|North Korea}}\n* [[Korean People's Army]]: Small number of IS-2s; never deployed in combat in the Korean War.\n;{{Flag|Poland}}\n* [[Polish Land Forces]]: Approximately 71 IS-2s used in combat between 1944-1945. 180 IS-2s survived as of 1955, and remained in service until the 1960s; some later were converted to [[armoured recovery vehicle]]s.\n;{{Flag|Romania}}\n* [[Romanian Land Forces]]: At least one IS-2 captured during May\u2013June 1944.<ref>Mark Axworthy, Cornel I. Scafe\u0219, Cristian Cr\u0103ciunoiu, ''Third Axis, Fourth Ally: Romanian Armed Forces in the European War, 1941-1945'', p. 221</ref>\n;{{Flag|South Ossetia}}\n* [[South Ossetian Army]]: Operated some IS-2s until 1995.\n;{{Flag|USSR}}\n* [[Red Army]]: Heavy Breakthrough Tank from 1944-1945.\n* [[Soviet Army]]: Phased out of service in the early-1970s.\n\n==Surviving vehicles==\nThere are several surviving IS-1 and IS-2 tanks, with examples found at the following:\n; IS-2\n* Os. G\u00f3rali [standing tank], Krak\u00f3w, Poland\n* [[Polish Army Museum]], Warsaw, Poland\n* Museum of Arms in [[Fort Winiary]], Pozna\u0144, Poland\n* Museum of Armoured Weapon in Training Center of Land Forces, Pozna\u0144, Poland (operational, [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_dXGjrqEZZ4 see movie])\n* Tank Museum of the People's Liberation Army, Beijing, China.\n* Liberty Park, Overloon, The Netherlands.\n* [[Museum of The History of Ukraine in World War II]], Ukraine\n* Kurzeme Fortress Museum, Zante, Latvia.\n* Diorama Battle of Kursk, in Belgorod, Russia.\n* The [[American Heritage Museum]], [[Stow, Massachusetts]], USA\n; IS-2M\n* [[Military museum Le\u0161any|Army Technical Museum]], Le\u0161any, Czech Republic<ref name=\"lesany\">[http://vhu.cz/cs/stranka/vojenske-technicke-muzeum] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505222057/http://vhu.cz/cs/stranka/vojenske-technicke-muzeum |date=May 5, 2009 }}</ref> (previously in Prague as a [[Monument to Soviet tank crews]])\n* [[Imperial War Museum Duxford]], England.\n* [[Kubinka Tank Museum]], Russia.\n* Victory Park at Poklonnaya Gora, Moscow, Russia.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=Notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|list}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Heavy tanks of the Soviet Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the predecessor to the IS-2 in the tank series|Kliment Voroshilov tank}}\n{{redirect-distinguish|IS2|ISIS (disambiguation){{!}}ISIS|ISS (disambiguation){{!}}ISS|i2s}}\n{{short description|Soviet WWII heavy tank}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name = IS-2\n|image = [[File:IS-2 Model 1943 - Sevastopol.png|300px]]\n|caption = IS-2 Model 1943, in [[Sevastopol]].\n|type = [[Heavy tank]]\n| origin             = [[Soviet Union]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = Yes\n| is_artillery       = Yes\n| is_vehicle         = Yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n|wars = {{plainlist|\n* [[World War II]]\n* [[Korean War]]}}\n|designer = [[Zhozef Kotin]]<br />[[Nikolay Dukhov]]\n|number = {{plainlist|\n* 3,854}}\n|spec_label = IS-2 Model 1944<ref>Zaloga 1984, p 176.</ref>\n|length = {{convert|9.90|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|width = {{convert|3.09|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|height = {{convert|2.73|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|used_by = {{plainlist|\n* [[Soviet Union]]\n* [[China]]\n* [[Cuba]]\n* [[Czechoslovakia]]\n* [[DPRK]]}}\n|design_date = {{plainlist|\n* 1943}}\n|manufacturer = [[Kirov Factory]], [[UZTM]]\n|unit_cost = IS-2 Model 1944: 264,400 rubles<ref name=\"tank\">{{cite web|url=http://tank.uw.ru/archive/sebestoimostx/|website=tank.uw.ru|title=\u0421\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u0445 \u0442\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430\u043c|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n|production_date = {{plainlist|\n* 1943\u201345}}\n|variants =\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight = {{convert|46|t|ST LT|lk=out}}\n|crew = 4\n<!-- Artillery specifications -->\n|elevation =\n|traverse =\n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n|armour = '''IS-2 Model 1944:'''<br />Hull front: 100&nbsp;mm at 60\u00b0 angle<br />Lower glacis: 100&nbsp;mm at 30\u00b0 angle<br />Turret front: 100 mm (rounded)<br />Mantlet: 155 mm (rounded)<br />Hull side: 90\u2013130 mm at 9-25\u00b0<br />Turret side: 90 mm at 20\u00b0 angle.\n|primary_armament = [[122 mm gun M1931/37 (A-19)|D25-T]] 122 mm gun (28 rounds)\n|secondary_armament = 1\u00d7[[DShK]], 3\u00d7[[Degtyarev light machine gun|DT]] (2,079 rounds)\n|engine = 12-cyl. diesel [[Kharkiv model V-2|model V-2]]\n|engine_power = 600 hp (450 kW)\n|pw_ratio = 13 hp/tonne\n|transmission =\n|suspension = [[torsion bar]]\n|clearance =\n|fuel_capacity = {{convert|820|l|abbr=on}}\n|vehicle_range = {{convert|240|km|abbr=on}}\n|speed = {{convert|37|km/h|abbr=on}}\n}}\n{{Cold War tanks}}\nThe '''IS-1''', redesignated the '''IS-2''' for security reasons, is the first [[Soviet]] [[heavy tank]] model of the [[IS tank series]].  It saw combat in [[World War II]] as well as service in other Soviet allied countries after the war.\n\n==Design and production==\n=== Object 237 KV-85 and IS-85/IS-1 ===\n{{anchor |Object 237|IS-85|IS-1}}\n[[File:KV-85 right side view.JPG|left|thumb|The KV-85 was a stop-gap solution until the introduction of the IS series. Note the modified [[Kliment Voroshilov tank|KV]] chassis with the removal of the hull machine-gunner/radio operator's station with one operated by the driver, and the driver's station slightly centered at the front; a staple design of all IS-series tank.]]\n[[File:IS 1 prototyp.jpg|thumbnail|IS-85 (IS-1) Prototype equipped with [[85 mm air defense gun M1939 (52-K)|D-5T]] gun. Later IS-2 converted models were replaced with the [[122 mm gun M1931/37 (A-19)|122mm D-25T gun]] whilst retaining the same hull.]]\nThe [[Kliment Voroshilov tank|KV-1]] was criticized by its crews for its poor mobility and the lack of a larger caliber gun than the [[T-34]] medium tank. It was much more expensive than the T-34, without having greater combat performance. Moscow ordered some KV-1 assembly lines to shift to T-34 production, leading to fears that KV-1 production would be halted and the SKB-2 design bureau, led by Kotin, closed.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1994|p=4}} In 1942, this problem was partially addressed by the KV-1S tank, which had thinner armor than the original, making it lighter and faster. It was competitive with the T-34 but at the cost of no longer having the heavier armor. Production of the KV-1S was gradually replaced by the [[SU-152]]{{Sfn|Zaloga|1996|p=44}} and ended in April 1943.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1996|p=42}}\n\nThe capture of a German [[Tiger I|Tiger]] tank in January 1943 led to a decision to develop a new heavy tank, which was given the codename Object 237.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1994|p=5}} Before Object 237 had time to mature, intense tank fighting in the summer of 1943 demanded a response. Dukhov's team was instructed to create a [[wikt:stopgap#Pronunciation|stopgap]] KV tank, the KV-85, which was armed with the [[85 mm air defense gun M1939 (52-K)|52-K]]-derivative gun of the [[SU-85]], the 85&nbsp;mm D-5T, that proved capable of penetrating the [[Tiger I]] from {{convert|1000|m|yd|abbr=on}}. The KV-85 was created by mounting an Object 237 turret on a KV-1S hull. To accommodate the Object 237 turret, the KV-1S hull was modified, increasing the diameter of the turret ring with fillets on the sides of the hull. The radio operator was replaced with an ammunition rack for the larger 85&nbsp;mm ammunition. The hull MG was then moved to the opposite side of the driver and fixed in place to be operated by the driver. From September to October 1943, a total of 130 KV-85s were produced, before the assembly lines began to shift over. Like the KV-1S, the KV-85 served in dwindling numbers and was quickly overshadowed by the superior IS series.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1996|p=45}}\n\nThe Object 237 prototype, a version of the cancelled [[KV-13]], was accepted for production as the '''IS-85''' heavy tank.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1994|p=6}} First deliveries were made in October 1943, and the tanks went immediately into service. Production ended in January 1944. Its designation was simplified to IS-1 after the introduction of the IS-122, later renamed as IS-2 for security purposes.\n\n===Object 240 IS-2===\n==== Gun ====\nBy 1943, engineers had succeeded in mounting the 85&nbsp;mm gun to the T-34 medium tank, making it as well-armed as the KV-85 heavy tank. Efforts to up-gun the IS-85 began in late 1943. Two candidate weapons were the D-25 122&nbsp;mm tank gun, the ballistic characteristics of which were identical to the [[122 mm gun M1931/37 (A-19)|A-19 122&nbsp;mm gun]],<ref name=Testing/> and the [[D-10 tank gun|D-10 100&nbsp;mm gun]], which was based on a naval [[dual-purpose gun]]. The D-10 had been designed for anti-tank fire and had better armor penetration than the A-19, but the smaller caliber meant it had a less useful [[High explosives|high explosive]] round. Also, the D-10 was a relatively new weapon in short supply, while there was excess production capacity for the A-19 and its ammunition. Compared to the older [[F-34 tank gun|F-34 76.2&nbsp;mm]] tank gun, the D-25 delivered 5.37 times the muzzle energy.\n\nAfter testing both the D-25 and D-10 on the IS-122, the former was selected as the main armament of the new tank. The D-25 used a separate shell and powder charge, resulting in a lower rate of fire compared to the single-piece ammunition used in most tanks, a serious disadvantage in tank-to-tank engagements. Soviet proving-ground tests showed that the D-25 could penetrate the front armor of the German [[Panther tank|Panther]] at {{convert|2500|m|yd|abbr=on}} while the D-10 could do so at a maximum range of {{convert|1500|m|yd|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Testing>{{cite web|title=Report on the results of testing of the 100 mm and the 122 mm tank guns at the Kubinka proving grounds|url=http://english.battlefield.ru/documents/29-technics/96-testing-100-mm-and-122-mm-tank-guns.html|website=The Russian Battlefield|accessdate=27 October 2014 |date=September 12, 1944 |last1=Tolochkov |last2=Volosatov}}</ref><ref>Zaloga 1984:172</ref> It was therefore considered an adequate anti-tank gun. First deliveries of IS-122s mounted with this gun were in December of 1943.<ref name=IS1+2 />\n\n[[File:D25T shells.svg|left|thumb|Projectiles and charges of the separate-loading ammunition of the A-19/D-25T 122mm gun. Left to right: cartridge case, high-explosive/fragmentation shell OF-471, armor-piercing high explosive shell BR-471, armor-piercing ballistic capped shell BR-471B. All shells are shown from two sides.]]\n\nA Wa Pruef 1 Report dated 5 October 1944 has data on the penetration ranges of the 122&nbsp;mm A-19 gun against a Panther tank angled at 30 degrees; this estimated that the A-19 gun was unable to penetrate the upper glacis plate of the Panther from any distance, could penetrate the lower glacis plate from {{convert|100|m|yd|abbr=on}}, could penetrate the mantlet from {{convert|500|m|yd|abbr=on}} and could penetrate the front turret from {{convert|1500|m|yd|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Panther128>{{cite book|last1=Jentz|first1=Thomas|title=Germany's Panther Tank: The Quest for Combat Supremacy|date=1995|publisher=Schiffer Military History|isbn=0887408125|page=128}}</ref> The Panther's {{convert|40|\u2013|50|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick side armor would have been exposed and vulnerable at such an angle; the sides at 30 degrees were penetrable from over {{convert|3500|m|yd|abbr=on}} according to the same Wa Pruef 1 report.<ref name=Panther128/> Testing with captured [[Tiger II|Tiger Ausf Bs]] in [[Kubinka]] showed that the 122&nbsp;mm D-25T was capable of penetrating the [[Tiger II|Tiger Ausf B's]] turret from {{convert|1000|\u2013|1500|m|yd|abbr=on}} and the weld joint or edges of the front hull plates at ranges of {{convert|500|\u2013|600|m|yd|abbr=on}}.<ref name=WasTheTigerReallyKing>{{cite web |url=http://english.battlefield.ru/analytics/126-was-the-tiger-really-king.html |title=Was the Tiger really King?|work=The Russian Battlefield|accessdate= 24 October 2014}}</ref> In 1944, the BR-471 was the sole armor-piercing round available. An improved version, the BR-471B ({{lang-ru|\u0411\u0420-471\u0411|links=no}}) was developed in spring 1945, but was available in quantity only after World War II ended.<ref>David R. Higgins, \"King Tiger vs IS-2: Operation Solstice 1945\", p. 29</ref>\n\nAccording to the same Wa Pruef 1 report, it was estimated that at 30 degree obliquity the hull armor of the Soviet [[IS-2]] model 1943 would be defeated by [[Tiger I]] between {{convert|100|and|300|m|mi|abbr=on}} at the driver's front plate and nose,{{sfn|Jentz|Doyle|1993|pp=19\u201320}} while the IS-2's 122&nbsp;mm gun would penetrate the Tiger's front armor from between {{convert|500|and|1500|m|mi|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Jentz|Doyle|1993|pp=19\u201320}} A Panther had to close to {{convert|600|m|yards|abbr=on}} to guarantee penetration of the IS-2's frontal armor (The Panther's 75&nbsp;mm gun could penetrate the IS-2 model 1943's mantlet from {{convert|400|m|yards|abbr=on}}, front turret from {{convert|800|m|yards|abbr=on}}, and driver's front plate from {{convert|600|m|yards|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Jentz 1995 p. 128\">Jentz 1995, p. 128</ref>), while the IS-2 could penetrate the Panther at ranges of {{convert|1000|m|yards|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref group=Notes>The German military intelligence journal for tank crews \"Nachrichtenblatt der Panzertruppen Nr.12, June 1944 p. 34\" reported that the IS-2 could be successful attacked at approximately {{convert|500|m|yd|abbr=on}} at the angle of 30 degrees. This calculation was derived from firing tables \"Pz. Beschusstafel\" created against the KV-85. Steven Zaloga makes therefore an unfavorable comparison (30\u00b0 to 90\u00b0 for the range of destruction) for the Panther over its adversary</ref> However, in the summer of 1944, the Germans experienced a shortage of manganese and had to switch to using high-carbon steel alloyed with nickel, which made armor very brittle, especially at the seam welds. The performance of the 122&nbsp;mm AP shells of the IS-2 against the Panther improved considerably. The reports from the front described cases where the BR-471 APHE round 122&nbsp;mm projectile fired from {{convert|2500|m|yd|abbr=on}} ricocheted off the front armor of a Panther, leaving huge breaches to it.<ref name=\"IS1+2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.battlefield.ru/js1-js2/stranitsa-3.html |title=IS-1 and IS-2 Heavy tanks |work=The Russian Battlefield|accessdate= 20 March 2017 |date=20 September 2005 |quote=source: Valery Potapov.}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=March 2017}} According to Steven Zaloga, the IS-2<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite book|last1=Zaloga|first1=Steven|title=IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944-73|date=1994|publisher=Osprey |page=12}}</ref> and Tiger I could knock each other out in normal combat distances below {{convert|1000|m|yd|abbr=on}}. At any range, the performance of each tank against each other was dependent on the crew and combat situation.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zaloga|first1=Steven|title=IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944\u201373|date=1994|publisher=Osprey |page=13}}</ref>\n\n[[File:IS-2 scheme.jpg|thumb|Line drawing of IS-2]]\nThe large 122&nbsp;mm [[High explosive|HE]] shell was its main asset, proving highly useful and destructive as an infantry-killer. In extremis, the IS-2 engaged enemy heavy armor with OF-471 ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u0424-471|links=no}}) high explosive projectiles. These shells had a mass of {{convert|25|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, a muzzle velocity of {{cvt|800|m/s|ft/s}}, and were equipped with a {{convert|3.8|kg|lb|abbr=on}} [[TNT]] charge. The explosive power could blow off an enemy tank turret, drive sprocket and tread off the heaviest German tank even if it could not penetrate the armor.<ref name=\"books.google.com.vn\"/><ref name=\"books.google.com.vn\"/><ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=The Encyclopedia of Weapons of World War II|author=Bishop, C.|date=2002|publisher=MetroBooks|isbn=9781586637620|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MuGsf0psjvcC&pg=PA41|page=41|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"google\"/> Mechanical shock and explosion was often enough to knock out enemy heavy tanks.<ref name=\"books.google.com.vn\">{{cite book|title=Soviet Heavy Tanks: World War 2 In Review Special|author=Merriam, R.|date=2016|publisher=Merriam Press|isbn=9781576385814|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RLjQDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA5|page=5|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe most recognizable disadvantage of the D-25T gun was its slow rate of fire due to the large size and weight of the shells; only one to one and a half rounds per minute could be fired, initially.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=D-25 Tank gun|url=http://www.battlefield.ru/d25.html|website=The Russian Battlfield|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> After some design improvements, including a semi-automatic drop breech over the previously manual screw breech, the rate of fire increased to 2\u20133 rounds per minute.<ref name=\"auto\"/> According to other sources, the increase may have amounted to 3\u20134 rounds per minute.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zaloga|first1=Steven|title=IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944-73|date=1994|publisher=Osprey Publishing Ltd.|isbn=9781849084055|page=41}}</ref> Another limitation imposed by the size of its ammunition in a relatively small vehicle was the ammunition stowage: only 28 rounds could be carried inside the tank, with a complement of 20 HE rounds and 8 AP rounds the norm.<ref>Zaloga 1984:175</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Higgins|first1=David|title=Kingtiger vs. IS-2|date=2011|publisher=Osprey |isbn=9781849084055 |page=74}}</ref>\n\n==== Production ====\nThe IS-122 prototype replaced the IS-85 and began mass production as the IS-2. The 85&nbsp;mm guns could be reserved for the new T-34-85 medium tank and some of the IS-1s built were rearmed before leaving the factory and issued as IS-2s. It was slightly lighter and faster than the heaviest KV model 1942 tank, with thicker front armor and a much-improved turret design. The tank could carry thicker armor than the KV series, while remaining lighter, due to the better layout of the armor envelope. The KV's armor was less well-shaped and featured heavy armor even on the rear, while the IS series concentrated its armor at the front. The IS-2 was slightly heavier than the Panther, much lighter than the [[Tiger I]] and [[Tiger II]] and had a lower silhouette than both. Western observers tended to criticize Soviet tanks for their lack of finish and crude construction. The Soviets argued that it was warranted, considering the need for wartime expediency and the typically short battlefield life of their tanks.<ref>Perrett 1987:20</ref>\n\n[[File:IS-2 scheme of armour.jpg|thumb|Armor plan of IS-2, models 1943 (top) and 1944 (bottom).]]\nEarly IS-2s can be identified by the 'stepped' front hull casting with its small, opening driver's visor. The early tanks lacked gun tube travel locks or anti-aircraft-capable machine guns and had narrow mantlets.\n\nIn late 1944, the stepped hull front was replaced with an improved single casting of 120&nbsp;mm thickness angled at 60 degrees. This new nose lacked the opening driver's visor. It is sometimes incorrectly referred to as the IS-2M, but that designation actually refers to a much later modernization program from the 1950s. Other minor upgrades included the addition of a travel lock on the hull rear, wider mantlet and, on very late models, an [[DShK|anti-aircraft machine gun]].\n\nIn comparison to the Tiger I, the IS-2 had modest advantages in armour, even though it was 10 tons lighter<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zaloga|first1=Steven|title=IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944\u201373|date=1994|publisher=Osprey |page=25}}</ref> In 1944, IS-2 tank was the only large-scale Allied tank whose armor provided some protection from the well-known Tiger 88mm long-barreled guns and Panther 75mm L/70 guns.\n\nIn the mid-1950s, the remaining IS-2 tanks (mostly model 1944 variants) were upgraded to the IS-2M standard, which introduced fittings such as external fuel tanks on the rear hull (the basic IS-2 had these only on the hull sides), stowage bins on both sides of the hull and protective skirting along the top edges of the [[Caterpillar track|tracks]].\n\n== Combat history ==\nThe IS-2 tank first saw combat in early 1944, equipping Guards Heavy Tank Regiments of the Red Army. First encountered by [[Otto Carius]] and a fellow Tiger I. After knocking out a column of T-34's, Carius moved into the nearby village of Malinava where he came face to face with the new IS-2. It was quickly destroyed, however as Carius moved further into the village he discovered a platoon of IS-2s. {{citation needed}} A regiment had 21 IS-2 tanks in four companies of five tanks each and one being used by the regimental commander.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1994|p=8}} The special tank regiments were reserved for important attacks, often to spearhead attempts to break through fortified German positions like anti-tank defence lines and bunkers.{{Sfn|Zaloga|1994|p=8}} The tanks supporting infantry in the assault by destroying bunkers, buildings, dug-in weapons and engaging German armoured vehicles. Once a breakthrough was achieved, lighter and more mobile tanks were used for exploitation and mopping-up. The IS-2 tank first saw action in [[Ukraine]] in early 1944 and claimed to have destroyed more than forty Tigers and [[Elefant]]s for the loss of only eight tanks. While the German heavy tanks could knock out the IS-2, they had no real answer to its {{nowrap|122 mm}} gun, which easily outgunned them.<ref>Tiger I and Tiger II. [[Anthony Tucker-Jones]]. Pen and Sword, 2013. {{ISBN|1473826780}}. P 160</ref>\n\n=== Ogl\u0119d\u00f3w ===\nOn the morning of 11 August 1944, the 16th Panzer Division attacked the 53d Guards Tank Brigade reinforced by the 71st Independent Guards Heavy Tank Regiment in the town of [[Ogl\u0119d\u00f3w]], toward Stasz\u00f3w. The extremely sandy terrain forced the eleven King Tigers to keep to the roads, whilst the defending Soviet forces positioned their tanks and assault guns in ambush positions and concentrated on the known German avenues of approach.<ref>Sledgehammers: Strengths and Flaws of Tiger Tank Battalions in World War II. Christopher W. Wilbeck. Aberjona, 2004. p.134</ref> When the attack started, three Tiger IIs were destroyed by fire from Soviet IS-2 tanks and one more Tiger II was knocked out a few hours later by a T-34/76 at a range of less than 400 meters. Later in the day, Soviet forces counter-attacked and seized the town of [[Ogl\u0119d\u00f3w]] and found three abandoned Tiger IIs. The capture of these tanks allowed the Soviets to conduct tests at Kubinka and to evaluate its strengths and weaknesses.<ref name=\"Sledgehammers 2004. p.135\">Sledgehammers: Strengths and Flaws of Tiger Tank Battalions in World War II. Christopher W. Wilbeck. Aberjona, 2004. p.135</ref>\n\nOver the next two days the Red Army advanced on Stasz\u00f3w and in several counter-attacks, Heavy Tank Battalion 501 lost seven more Tiger IIs. Virtually all of these were destroyed by Soviet tanks occupying a defensive position against those German attacks.<ref name=\"Sledgehammers 2004. p.135\"/> In three days of fighting, Soviet forces destroyed or captured 14 of 30 Tiger IIs to an approximately equal number of Soviet IS-2s and T-34s.<ref name=\"Sledgehammers 2004. p.135\"/><ref>{{cite|title=Hitler's Panzers: The Lightning Attacks that Revolutionized Warfare|first1=Dennis |last1=Showalter|publisher=Penguin|date=2009|page=315|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Mcx7PGEdSKAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Hitler%27s+Panzers:+The+Lightning+Attacks+that+Revolutionized+Warfare&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwia8KGgoO7XAhXmIMAKHaeNCxEQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=501st%20Heavy%20Tank%20battalion&f=false|isbn=978-0425236895}}</ref>\n\n\n=== Post World War II ===\nBy the 1950s, the emergence of the [[main battle tank]] concept\u2014combining medium-tank mobility with the firepower and armor of the heavy tank\u2014had rendered heavy tanks obsolete. In the late 1960s the remaining Soviet heavy tanks were transferred to Red Army reserve service and storage. The IS-2 Model 1944 remained in service much longer in the armies of [[Cuba]], [[China]] and [[North Korea]]. A regiment of Chinese IS-2s was available for use in the [[Korean War]] but saw no service there.\n\nAfter the Korean War, China attempted to reverse-engineer the IS-2/IS-3 as the Type 122 medium tank. The project was cancelled in favor of the [[Type 59 tank|Type 59]], a copy of the Soviet T-54A\n\n== Variants ==\n;KV-85: A stopgap model built from a modified KV-1S hull mated to an Object 237(IS-1)'s turret and armed with the 85&nbsp;mm D-5T.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zaloga|first1=Steven|title=IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944-1944|date=1994|publisher=Osprey Publishing Ltd.|isbn=1855323966|pages=5\u20136}}</ref>\n;IS-85 (IS-1): 1943 model armed with an 85&nbsp;mm gun. When IS-2 production started, many were re-gunned with 122&nbsp;mm guns before being issued.\n;IS-100: A prototype version armed with a 100&nbsp;mm gun; it went into trials against the ''IS-122'' which was armed with a 122&nbsp;mm gun. Though the IS-100 was reported to have better anti-armor capabilities, the latter was chosen due to better all-around performance.\n;IS-122 (IS-2 model 1943): 1943 model, armed with A-19 122&nbsp;mm gun.\n;IS-2 model 1944 (sometimes \"IS-2m\"):1944 improvement with D25-T 122&nbsp;mm gun, with faster-loading drop breech and new fire control, improved simpler hull front.\n;IS-2M: 1950s modernization of IS-2 tanks.\n\n==Operators==\n;{{Flag|China}}\n* [[People's Liberation Army]]: 60 IS-2s delivered in 1950\u20131951. Operated during the Korean War and in concrete bunkers along the Sino-Soviet border.\n;{{Flag|Cuba}}\n* [[Cuban Army]]: 41 IS-2Ms delivered in 1960.\n;{{Flag|Czechoslovakia}}\n* [[Czechoslovak Army]]: 8 IS-2/IS-2M in service between 1945-1960.\n;{{Flag|East Germany}}\n* [[National People's Army|NVA]]: 60 IS-2 delivered 1956. Operated until 1963.\n;{{Flag|Nazi Germany}}\n* [[Wehrmacht]]: Captured one or two IS-2 in May 1945.<ref>Das letzte Jahr der deutschen Heeres 1944-1945 \" von Wolfgang Fleischer / Podzun-Pallas Verlag</ref>\n;{{Flag|Hungary}}\n* [[Hungarian People's Army]]: 68 IS-2s in service between 1950-1956. After the crackdown of the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] all were returned to the Soviet Union.<ref>http://epa.oszk.hu/01600/01639/00008/pdf/EPA01639_elso_szazad_2012_tel_061-069.pdf</ref>\n;{{Flag|North Korea}}\n* [[Korean People's Army]]: Small number of IS-2s; never deployed in combat in the Korean War.\n;{{Flag|Poland}}\n* [[Polish Land Forces]]: Approximately 71 IS-2s used in combat between 1944-1945. 180 IS-2s survived as of 1955, and remained in service until the 1960s; some later were converted to [[armoured recovery vehicle]]s.\n;{{Flag|Romania}}\n* [[Romanian Land Forces]]: At least one IS-2 captured during May\u2013June 1944.<ref>Mark Axworthy, Cornel I. Scafe\u0219, Cristian Cr\u0103ciunoiu, ''Third Axis, Fourth Ally: Romanian Armed Forces in the European War, 1941-1945'', p. 221</ref>\n;{{Flag|South Ossetia}}\n* [[South Ossetian Army]]: Operated some IS-2s until 1995.\n;{{Flag|USSR}}\n* [[Red Army]]: Heavy Breakthrough Tank from 1944-1945.\n* [[Soviet Army]]: Phased out of service in the early-1970s.\n\n==Surviving vehicles==\nThere are several surviving IS-1 and IS-2 tanks, with examples found at the following:\n; IS-2\n* Os. G\u00f3rali [standing tank], Krak\u00f3w, Poland\n* [[Polish Army Museum]], Warsaw, Poland\n* Museum of Arms in [[Fort Winiary]], Pozna\u0144, Poland\n* Museum of Armoured Weapon in Training Center of Land Forces, Pozna\u0144, Poland (operational, [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_dXGjrqEZZ4 see movie])\n* Tank Museum of the People's Liberation Army, Beijing, China.\n* Liberty Park, Overloon, The Netherlands.\n* [[Museum of The History of Ukraine in World War II]], Ukraine\n* Kurzeme Fortress Museum, Zante, Latvia.\n* Diorama Battle of Kursk, in Belgorod, Russia.\n* The [[American Heritage Museum]], [[Stow, Massachusetts]], USA\n; IS-2M\n* [[Military museum Le\u0161any|Army Technical Museum]], Le\u0161any, Czech Republic<ref name=\"lesany\">[http://vhu.cz/cs/stranka/vojenske-technicke-muzeum] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505222057/http://vhu.cz/cs/stranka/vojenske-technicke-muzeum |date=May 5, 2009 }}</ref> (previously in Prague as a [[Monument to Soviet tank crews]])\n* [[Imperial War Museum Duxford]], England.\n* [[Kubinka Tank Museum]], Russia.\n* Victory Park at Poklonnaya Gora, Moscow, Russia.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=Notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|list}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Heavy tanks of the Soviet Union]]\n", "name_user": "AnonApril2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCombat history", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IS-1_and_IS-2"}
