ist (magazine)|Cyclist]]|publisher=Dennis Publishing Limited|date=3 December 2018|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n| majorwins     = '''[[Race stage|Stage races]]'''\n:[[Giro d'Italia Femminile]] ([[2015 Giro d'Italia Femminile|2015]], [[2017 Giro d'Italia Femminile|2017]])\n::1 individual stage\n:[[Tour of California (women's race)|Tour of California]] ([[2017 Tour of California (women's race)|2017]], [[2019 Tour of California (women's race)|2019]])\n:[[Ladies Tour of Norway]] ([[2014 Ladies Tour of Norway|2014]])\n:[[Festival Luxembourgeois du cyclisme f\u00e9minin Elsy Jacobs|Grand Prix Elsy Jacobs]] ([[2014 Festival Luxembourgeois du cyclisme f\u00e9minin Elsy Jacobs|2014]], [[2015 Festival Luxembourgeois du cyclisme f\u00e9minin Elsy Jacobs|2015]])\n:[[Tour de Bretagne]] (2012)\n'''[[Classic cycle races|One-day races and Classics]]'''\n:[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's individual road race|Olympic Road Race]] ([[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's individual road race|2016]])\n:[[UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|World Road Race Championships]] ([[2018 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|2018]])\n:[[Tour of Flanders for Women|Tour of Flanders]] ([[2018 Tour of Flanders for Women|2018]])\n:[[Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge (women's race)|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]] ([[2017 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge (women's race)|2017]], [[2018 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge (women's race)|2018]])\n:[[La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne F\u00e9minine|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]] ([[2015 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne F\u00e9minine|2015]], [[2016 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne F\u00e9minine|2016]], [[2017 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne F\u00e9minine|2017]], [[2018 Fl\u00e8che Wallonne (women's race)|2018]], [[2019 Fl\u00e8che Wallonne (women's race)|2019]])\n:[[Amstel Gold Race (women's race)|Amstel Gold Race]] ([[2017 Amstel Gold Race (women's race)|2017]])\n:[[Strade Bianche Donne|Strade Bianche]] ([[2018 Strade Bianche Women|2018]])\n:[[GP de Plouay]] ([[2019 GP de Plouay|2019]])\n:[[Omloop Het Nieuwsblad]] ([[2015 Omloop Het Nieuwsblad \u2013 Women's race|2015]])\n:[[La Course by Le Tour de France]] ([[2015 La Course by Le Tour de France|2015]])\n:[[Dutch National Time Trial Championships|National Time Trial Championships]] (2015)\n:{{nowrap|[[European Road Championships#Women.27s road race|European Road Race Championships]] (2016)}}\n:[[European Road Championships#Women.27s time trial|European U-23 Time Trial Championships]] (2012)\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[road bicycle racing|road cycling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| the {{NED}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|Olympic Games}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's individual road race|Road race]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's road time trial|Time trial]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Road World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold  |[[2018 UCI Road World Championships|2018 Innsbruck]]|[[2018 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|Road race]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[2015 UCI Road World Championships|2015 Richmond]]|[[2015 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|Road race]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[2015 UCI Road World Championships|2015 Richmond]]|[[2015 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|Time trial]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[2017 UCI Road World Championships|2017 Bergen]]|[[2017 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|Time trial]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[2018 UCI Road World Championships|2018 Innsbruck]]|[[2018 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|Time trial]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[2019 UCI Road World Championships|2019 Harrogate]]|[[2019 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|Time trial]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Road Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold |[[2016 European Road Championships|2016 Plumelec]]|[[2016 European Road Championships \u2013 Women's road trial|Road race]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[2016 European Road Championships|2016 Plumelec]]|[[2016 European Road Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|Time trial]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[2018 European Road Championships|2018 Glasgow]]|[[2018 European Road Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|Time trial]]}}\n{{MedalBronze |[[2017 European Road Championships|2017 Herning]]|[[2017 European Road Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|Time trial]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2015 European Games|2015 Baku]]|[[Cycling at the 2015 European Games \u2013 Women's road race|Road race]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| {{ct|NLB|2015}} (2015)<br>{{ct|DLT|2018}} (2017\u20132018)}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Road World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze |[[2015 UCI Road World Championships|2015 Richmond]]|[[2015 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's team time trial|Team time trial]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[2017 UCI Road World Championships|2017 Bergen]]|[[2017 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's team time trial|Team time trial]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[2018 UCI Road World Championships|2018 Innsbruck]]|[[2018 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's team time trial|Team time trial]]}}\n| show-medals    =  no\n}}\n'''Anna van der Breggen''' (born 18 April 1990) is a Dutch professional [[Road bicycle racing|road bicycle racer]], who currently rides for [[UCI Women's Team|UCI Women's Continental Team]] {{ct|DLT}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/features/2020-team-preview-boels-dolmans/|title=2020 Team Preview: Boels Dolmans|first=Kirsten|last=Frattini|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref> She won the gold medal in the [[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's individual road race|women's road race]] at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]],<ref name=cw2016>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/racing/olympics/anna-van-der-breggen-wins-rio-2016-olympics-womens-road-race-272402|title=Anna van der Breggen wins Rio 2016 Olympics women's road race; Lizzie Armitstead fifth| website=[[Cycling Weekly]]|date=7 August 2016|last1=Wynn|first1=Nigel|access-date=8 August 2016}}</ref> and has won the [[Giro d'Italia Femminile]] on two occasions.<ref name=\"Giro2018\"/> In 2018, she won the [[2018 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|women's road race]] at the [[2018 UCI Road World Championships|UCI Road World Championships]].\n\nConsidered one of the most versatile riders of her generation, van der Breggen excels in both the [[classic cycle races|one-day classics]] and [[Race stage|stage races]], particularly when run on a hilly terrain. Apart from the Olympic road race title and two Giro Rosa titles, other notable wins include [[La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne F\u00e9minine|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]] on five consecutive occasions, [[Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge (women's race)|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]] two times, the [[Tour of Flanders for Women|Tour of Flanders]], [[Amstel Gold Race#Women's Race|Amstel Gold Race]], [[Strade Bianche Donne|Strade Bianche]], [[Omloop Het Nieuwsblad]] and the [[European Road Championships#Women.27s road race|European Road Race Championships]].<ref name=\"FW2018\"/><ref name=\"CT15\"/><ref name=\"AGR2017\"/><ref name=\"LBL2017\"/><ref name=\"Flanders2018\"/> In addition, she has won the general classification and numerous stages in smaller stage races.\n\nIn 2017, she won all three [[Ardennes classics]] races in one week, which earned her the nickname ''Queen of the Ardennes''.<ref name=\"CN Ardennes\"/> She went on to secure her second [[2017 Giro d'Italia Femminile|Giro d'Italia]] win the following summer.<ref name=\"Giro2018\"/> In April 2019, she won the [[La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne F\u00e9minine]], her fifth-consecutive win in the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/48044467 |title=Fleche Wallonne: Anna van der Breggen & Julian Alaphilippe win |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career ==\n\n===Early life and amateur career===\nAnna van der Breggen was born in [[Zwolle]] into a cycling family. She has three brothers and a sister who all practiced cycling at some point.<ref name=\"wielerflits1\"/> She started bike-racing at the age of seven with the local club ''WV Noordwesthoek'' and became more serious about it in the juniors category.<ref name=\"Onderweg\"/> In 2007, aged 17, she was fifth in the [[2007 UCI Road World Championships|juniors world championship road race]] in [[Aguascalientes City|Aguascalientes]] but had a difficult transition to the elite category.<ref>{{cite web|title=Italiaanse Patuzzo pakt titel in wegrit|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf12082007_064|website=[[De Standaard]]|publisher=[[Mediahuis]]|accessdate=18 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref> She considered quitting the sport after she suffered in the back of the peloton during the [[Grote Prijs Gerrie Knetemann]].<ref name=\"wielerflits1\"/>\n\n===2012\u20132013: Turning professional===\nVan der Breggen turned professional in 2012 with the {{ct|SLT|2012}}. In July, she won the [[Tour de Bretagne F\u00e9minin]]. She won three of the four stages and secured the overall classification with a lead of almost three minutes over [[Sofie De Vuyst]]. She also won the time trial at the [[Tour F\u00e9minin en Limousin]] as well as the gold medal in the women's under-23 time-trialling event at the [[2012 European Road Championships|European championships]]. As a result, she was selected for the [[2012 UCI Road World Championships|2012 World Championships]]. Whilst playing a domestique role for her team leader, [[Marianne Vos]], she managed to finish fifth herself in the [[2012 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|road race]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-2207219/Marianne-Vos-wins-womens-road-cycling-world-title.html?ito=feeds-newsxml|title=Vos proves she's the boss by becoming women's road cycling world champion|series=Sportsmail Reporter|work=Daily Mail|date=22 September 2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 she devoted herself to finishing her studies and rode a low-key season, with the highlight of the year a fourth place at the [[Trofeo Alfredo Binda-Comune di Cittiglio|Trofeo Alfredo Binda]]. After she obtained her [[nursing]] degree,<ref name=\"wielerflits1\">{{cite web|last1=Bender|first1=Richard|title=Weekendinterview: Anna van der Breggen|url=http://www.wielerflits.nl/nieuws/71624/weekendinterview-anna-van-der-breggen.html|website=wielerflits.nl|accessdate=16 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref> she became a full-time professional cyclist and finished 18th in the [[2013 Giro d'Italia Femminile|Giro Rosa]] in the summer. She was selected to compete in the [[2013 UCI Road World Championships|World Championships]] in [[Florence]] where she finished fourth in the [[2013 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|road race]].<ref name=\"Tissot2013\">{{cite web|url=http://cycling.sportresult.com/results/cr/2013/WM/11RES00.pdf|title=Final Results / R\u00e9sultats finaux: Road Race Women Elite / Course en ligne femmes \u00e9lite|work=Sport Result|publisher=[[Tissot|Tissot Timing]]|date=28 September 2013|accessdate=28 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012063031/http://cycling.sportresult.com/results/cr/2013/WM/11RES00.pdf|archive-date=12 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In preparation for the 2014 season, she announced she would be joining the {{ct|RBW|2014}} team.\n\n===2014: Stage race success===\n{{see also|2014 Rabo\u2013Liv Women Cycling Team season}}\nVan der Breggen's first season on the Rabo team proved highly fruitful. She opened the year with top-10 finishes in the [[2014 Ronde van Drenthe World Cup|Ronde van Drenthe]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/other-sports/cycling/help-from-van-dijk-elevates-armitstead-1-6502681|title=Help from van Dijk elevates Armitstead|newspaper=Yorkshire Post|date=14 March 2014|accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref> [[2014 Trofeo Alfredo Binda-Comune di Cittiglio|Trofeo Alfredo Binda]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/trofeo-alfredo-binda/2014 |title=2014: 16th Trofeo Alfredo Binda \u2013 Comune di Cittiglio (CDM) |work=ProCyclingStats |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> and the [[2014 Tour of Flanders for Women|Tour of Flanders]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Shea|first1=Sadhbh|title=Ellen van Dijk wins Tour of Flanders World Cup|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tour-of-flanders-women-2014/results/|website=[[Cyclingnews]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> and started showing her stage racing potential throughout the season. She claimed notable wins in the overall classification of both the [[2014 Ladies Tour of Norway|Ladies Tour of Norway]] and [[Grand Prix Elsy Jacobs]] in Luxembourg;<ref>http://women.cyclingfever.com/editie.html?editie_idd=MjUxNTE=</ref> as well as a runner-up spot in the [[2014 Lotto Belisol Belgium Tour|Belgium Tour]] and third places in the [[2014 Emakumeen Euskal Bira|Emakumeen Euskal Bira]] and the [[2014 Giro d'Italia Femminile|Giro Rosa]], in a podium made up entirely of {{ct|RBW|2014|nolink=yes}} riders.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Been|first1=Jos\u00e9|title=Vos secures Giro Rosa title, Pooley wins in Madonna del Ghisallo|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/giro-ditalia-internazionale-femminile-2014/stage-9/results/|website=[[Cyclingnews]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHer season came to an abrupt end when she broke her pelvis at the [[2014 UCI Road World Championships|UCI Road World Championships]] in [[Ponferrada]], Spain. Her teammate [[Annemiek van Vleuten]] crashed just before the finish of the [[2014 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's team time trial|Women's Team Time Trial]] after clipping the roadside barriers and brought down van der Breggen and two other riders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/cycling/11112211/Disaster-befalls-Marianne-Voss-Rabo-Liv-as-Specialized-Lululemon-seal-hat-trick-of-world-time-trial-titles.html| title=Disaster befalls Marianne Vos's Rabo-Liv as Specialized-Lululemon seal hat-trick of world time trial titles|work=Telegraph| date=21 September 2014|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref> Van der Breggen broke her [[Ilium (bone)|ilium]] and was transported to hospital.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breuk in darmbeen Van der Breggen na val in tijdrit|url=https://www.ad.nl/wielrennen/breuk-in-darmbeen-van-der-breggen-na-val-in-tijdrit~a11275c7/|website=[[Algemeen Dagblad]]|publisher=[[De Persgroep]]|accessdate=17 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n===2015: First Giro Rosa win===\n[[File:Gent - Omloop Het Nieuwsblad, 28 februari 2015 (C7).JPG|thumb|On the podium in [[Ghent]] after winning [[2015 Omloop Het Nieuwsblad \u2013 Women's race|2015 Omloop Het Nieuwsblad]]]]\nShe recovered from her [[pelvic fracture]] in the winter of 2015 and won her first [[classic cycle races|major classic]], the [[2015 Omloop Het Nieuwsblad \u2013 Women's race|Omloop Het Nieuwsblad]], in late February. Van der Breggen had broken away from a lead group together with [[Ellen van Dijk]] on the [[Molenberg (Zwalm)|Molenberg]], at {{convert|30|km|abbr=off}} from the finish. She beat her fellow Dutch in the sprint.<ref name=\"CT15\">{{cite news|url=http://cyclingtips.com.au/2015/03/anna-van-der-breggen-bests-ellen-van-dijk-in-european-opener/|title=Anna van der Breggen bests Ellen van Dijk in European opener|publisher=cyclingtips.com.au|date=28 February 2015|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> The following week, she was second in [[2015 Le Samyn des Dames|Le Samyn des Dames]].<ref>[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Le_Samyn_des_Dames_2015 Le Samyn des Dames 2015]</ref> In April she won [[2015 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne F\u00e9minine|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]] with an attack at the foot of the [[Mur de Huy]], and recorded several podium positions in one-day races.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rogers|first1=Owen|title=Anna van der Breggen wins women's Fleche Wallonne|work=[[Cycling Weekly]]|date=22 April 2015}}</ref> She highlighted her stage race potential again by taking the overall classification at the [[Grand Prix Elsy Jacobs]], which she led from the prologue to the end of the race.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/festival-luxembourgeois-du-cyclisme-fminin-elsy-jacobs-2015/prologue/results |title=Van Der Breggen wins prologue at Elsy Jacobs|date=1 May 2015 |website=[[cyclingnews.com]]|access-date=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June, she won the bronze medal in the [[Cycling at the 2015 European Games \u2013 Women's road race|women's road race]] at the [[European Games 2015|inaugural European Games]] in [[Baku]]. She was part of a four-woman breakaway together with Ellen van Dijk, [[Katarzyna Niewiadoma]] and [[Alena Amialiusik]], when an acceleration by van der Breggen caused her teammate van Dijk to be dropped, for the race to be decided in a three-up sprint. Van der Breggen led out the sprint from afar but was passed by both Amialiusik and Niewiadoma.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pickering|first1=Stuart|title=European Games Baku \u2013 Amialiusik from a sprint!|url=https://cyclingdirect.co.za/news/european-games-baku-amialiusik-sprint|website=cyclingdirect.co.za|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Baku\">{{cite web |url=http://www.baku2015.com/cycling-road/index.html |title=Cycling Road at the 2015 European Games |accessdate=14 June 2015 |work=Baku 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910104340/http://www.baku2015.com/cycling-road/index.html |archive-date=10 September 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[File:La Course by Le Tour de France 2015 (19937935079).jpg|thumb|left|Van der Breggen soloed to victory at the [[2015 La Course by Le Tour de France|second La Course]] on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in Paris.]]\nVan der Breggen claimed her greatest career victory to that point in July when she won the general classification at the [[2015 Giro d'Italia Femminile|Giro d'Italia Femminile]], the most important stage race on the women's calendar and the only [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]] for women.<ref name=\"Stage 9\"/> She finished fourth in the prologue and second in stage 2,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/giro-rosa-2015/prologue/results | title=Giro Rosa: Van Vleuten wins prologue in Ljubljana | work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] | publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]] | date=3 July 2015 | accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref> after which she remained in the top-three until the Alpine stages. Van der Breggen was in third position overall behind [[maglia rosa]] wearer [[Megan Guarnier]], when she moved into the race lead on the penultimate day after winning the [[2015 Giro d'Italia Femminile#Stage 8 (ITT)|individual time trial]] to [[Nebbiuno]].<ref name=\"Stage 8\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/giro-rosa-2015/stage-8/results | title=Giro Rosa: Van der Breggen wins stage 8 time trial, moves into maglia rosa | work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] | publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]] | date=11 July 2015 | accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> She won the time trial more than one minute ahead of Guarnier and secured her overall win with a second place in the [[2015 Giro d'Italia Femminile#Stage 9|final stage]].<ref name=\"Stage 9\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/giro-rosa-2015/stage-9/results | title=Giro Rosa: Van der Breggen wins overall title | work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] | publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]] | date=12 July 2015 | accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> Later she won the second edition of [[2015 La Course by Le Tour de France|La Course by Le Tour de France]] on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Anna van der Breggen wins La Course as Lizzie Armitstead fades|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/jul/26/anna-van-der-breggen-la-course-lizzie-armitstead|website=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> and she won the final stage of the [[2015 Belgium Tour|Belgium Tour]] in [[Geraardsbergen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Van der Breggen wins final Lotto Belgium Tour stage|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/lotto-belgium-tour-2015/stage-4/results/|website=[[Cyclingnews]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2015 UCI Road World Championships|World Championships]] in September in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], she claimed the silver medals in both the [[2015 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|individual time trial]] and the [[2016 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|road race]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Armitstead wins women's World Championship road race|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/uci-road-world-championships-2015/elite-women-road-race/results/|website=Cyclingnews|publisher=Immediate Media Company|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref> She finished at two seconds from [[Linda Villumsen]] in the time trial,<ref>{{cite web|title=Linda Villumsen wins time-trial gold at World Championships|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/cycling/34329834|website=[[British Broadcasting Company|BBC]]|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref> and was narrowly beaten by [[Lizzie Deignan|Lizzie Armitstead]] in the road race after she started the sprint from afar.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Frattini|first1=Kristen|title=Van der Breggen fights to hide disappointment after losing the World Championship|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/van-der-breggen-fights-to-hide-disappointment-after-losing-the-world-championship/|website=Cyclingnews|publisher=Immediate Media Company|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref> She ended the year as second in the [[2015 UCI Women's Road World Cup|UCI Road World Cup]], behind Armitstead, and was awarded the Gerrit Schulte Trophy for best female Dutch cyclist of the year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Clarke|first=Stuart|title=Tom Dumoulin named Dutch Cyclist of the Year|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/tom-dumoulin-named-dutch-cyclist-of-the-year-202134|access-date=1 December 2015|work=[[Cycling Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc. UK]]|date=1 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2016: Olympic and European champion===\nVan der Breggen opened the 2016 season with 5th place at the [[2016 Strade Bianche Women|Strade Bianche]], 4th at the [[2016 Ronde van Drenthe|Ronde van Drenthe]] and 6th at the [[2016 Trofeo Alfredo Binda-Comune di Cittiglio|Trofeo Alfredo Binda]] in March;<ref>{{cite web|last1=Braverman|first1=Jessi|title=Lizzie Armitstead wins Strade Bianche Women|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/strade-bianche-women-2016/results/|website=cyclingnews.com|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bravermann|first1=Jessi|title=Armitstead wins Trofeo Alfredo Binda|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/trofeo-alfredo-binda-comune-di-cittiglio-2016/results/|website=[[Cyclingnews]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> but failed to claim a victory until she successfully defended her title at [[2016 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne F\u00e9minine|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]]. She counterattacked a move by [[Katarzyna Niewiadoma]] on the C\u00f4te de Cherave, at {{convert|10|km|abbr=off}} from the finish, and was followed by only four others over the top. She broke clear again with [[Evelyn Stevens]] at {{convert|3|km|abbr=off}} from the finish and powered away from Stevens on the finishing [[Mur de Huy]] to claim her second victory in succession.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Braverman|first1=Jessi|title=Van der Breggen wins La Fleche Wallonne Feminine. Dutchwoman attacks Stevens on the Mur de Huy|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/la-fleche-wallonne-feminine-2016/results/|website=[[Cyclingnews]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July, she finished third overall in the [[2016 Giro d'Italia Femminile|Giro Rosa]].<ref name=\"Giro16\">{{cite web|last1=Frattini|first1=Kristen|title=Guarnier wins 2016 Giro Rosa|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/giro-ditalia-internazionale-femminile-2016/stage-9/results/|website=[[Cyclingnews]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> She was third in the prologue,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/giro-ditalia-internazionale-femminile-2016/prologue/results/|title=Giro Rosa: Kirchmann claims prologue victory|website=[[Cyclingnews]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=3 July 2016}}</ref> but lost time in the mountain stages in the [[Dolomites]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Ciclismo/06-07-2016/giro-rosa-mortirolo-mara-abbott-longo-borghini-160250826782.shtml|title=Giro Rosa, il Mortirolo lancia Mara Abbott|website=[[Gazzetta dello Sport]]|language=Italian|accessdate=9 July 2016}}</ref> She climbed back to third place after finishing second in [[2016 Giro d'Italia Femminile#Stage 7|stage 7's individual time trial]] and held on to her podium place until the finish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/giro-ditalia-internazionale-femminile-2016/stage-7/results/|title=Stevens wins Giro Rosa time trial|website=Cyclingnews|accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Giro16\"/>\nDuring the Giro she announced she would leave {{ct|RBW|2016}} to join {{ct|DLT|2017}} for the 2017 season onwards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/boels-dolmans-announce-anna-van-der-breggen-signing/|title=Boels-Dolmans announce Anna van der Breggen signing - Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rio 2016 - Women's road race (29176432145).jpg|thumb|left|Anna van der Breggen during the podium ceremony of the [[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's individual road race|Olympic road race]] in [[Rio de Janeiro|Rio]] after winning the gold medal.]]\nOn 7 August 2016, van der Breggen won the gold medal in the [[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's individual road race|women's road race]] at the [[2016 Summer Olympics|Rio Olympics]].<ref name=cw2016/> On the final climb, the {{convert|9|km|abbr=off|adj=on}} long [[Vista Chinesa]], five riders had remained in the front: van der Breggen and her teammate Annemiek van Vleuten, American [[Mara Abbott]], Italian [[Elisa Longo Borghini]] and Sweden's [[Emma Johansson]]. Van Vleuten jumped away shortly before the top and only Abbott managed to join. In the sinuous descent that followed, van Vleuten distanced Abbott and looked on her way to win the race, when she crashed into a concrete banking with {{convert|10|km|abbr=off}} to go and needed to be transported to hospital. Suddenly Abbott seemed on her way to Olympic glory but she was caught back by the three upcoming riders at {{convert|500|m|abbr=off}} from the finish. Van der Breggen beat Johansson and Longo Borghini in the three-up sprint on [[Copacabana, Rio de Janeiro|Copacabana Beach]] to become Olympic road race champion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Van der Breggen wint goud na dramatische val Van Vleuten|url=https://nos.nl/rio2016/artikel/2123839-van-der-breggen-wint-goud-na-dramatische-val-van-vleuten.html|website=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]]|accessdate=15 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref> Three days later she won the bronze medal in the [[Cycling at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's road time trial|individual time trial]], 11 seconds behind winner [[Kristin Armstrong]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/cycling-road-standings-cr-womens-individual-time-trial |title=Women's Individual Time Trial  \u2013 Standings |work=Rio2016 |date=11 August 2016 |accessdate=11 August 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806051845/https://www.rio2016.com/en/cycling-road-standings-cr-womens-individual-time-trial |archivedate= 6 August 2016 }}</ref> Following her Olympic success, she was [[Knight of the Order of Orange-Nassau|knighted in the Order of Orange-Nassau]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/van-der-breggen-and-ligtlee-given-royal-honours-news-shorts/ |title=Van der Breggen and Ligtlee given royal honours \u2013 News shorts|date=24 August 2016 |website=[[cyclingnews.com]] |access-date=29 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-September, she took part in the [[2016 European Road Championships|European Road Championships]]. She finished second in the [[2016 European Road Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|time trial]] behind [[Ellen van Dijk]].<ref name=\"CN\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/uec-road-european-championship-2016/u23-and-elite-women-time-trial/results/|title=European Championships: Van Dijk wins women's time trial|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|date=15 September 2016|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref> In the road race she followed an acceleration of Niewiadoma on the final climb, together with Longo Borghini, [[Alena Amialiusik]] and [[Rasa Leleivyt\u0117]]. Van der Breggen launched the five-woman sprint from afar and became the first ever professional European road race champion.<ref>{{cite web|title=EK 2016: Anna van der Breggen pakt Europese titel|url=http://www.wielerflits.nl/nieuws/208932/ek-2016-anna-van-der-breggen-pakt-europese-titel.html|website=wielerflits.nl|accessdate=16 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref> At the [[2016 UCI Road World Championships|World Championships]] in October, she was a disappointing 13th in the [[2016 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|time trial]] and 87th in the [[2016 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|road race]],<ref name=\"2016women\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/uci-road-world-championships-2016/elite-women-road-race/ |title=2016 Road World Championships Elite Women's Road Race |accessdate=15 October 2016 |work=Cycling News}}</ref> telling reporters she \"didn't have the legs anymore after a long season\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=IJnsen|first1=Youri|title=Teleurstelling heerst bij Nederlandse vrouwen|url=http://www.wielerflits.nl/nieuws/213485/teleurstelling-heerst-bij-nederlandse-vrouwen.html|website=Wielerflits.nl|accessdate=16 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n===2017: Ardennes Trio and second Giro win===\n[[File:2017 Boels Ladies Tour 6e etappe 068a.jpg|thumb|right|Van der Breggen ended 2017 as winner of the [[2017 UCI Women's World Tour|Women's World Tour]] ''(pictured in the World Tour leader's jersey at the [[2017 Holland Ladies Tour]])'']]\nAfter placing 15th in both the [[2017 Ronde van Drenthe|Ronde van Drenthe]] and the [[2017 Tour of Flanders for Women|Tour of Flanders]], and finishing second overall in the [[2017 Healthy Ageing Tour|Healthy Ageing Tour]] in early 2017, van der Breggen became the first woman to win all three of the [[Ardennes classics]] in a single year. She won the rebooted [[2017 Amstel Gold Race (women's race)|Amstel Gold Race]] with an attack at {{convert|8|km|abbr=off}} from the finish.<ref name=\"AGR2017\">{{cite web|last1=Braverman|first1=Jessi|title=Van der Breggen wins women's Amstel Gold Race|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/amstel-gold-race-women-2017/results/|website=Cyclingnews|publisher=Immediate Media Company|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> Three days later, she secured her third straight [[2017 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne F\u00e9minine|Fl\u00e8che Wallonne win]] after powering away on the [[Mur de Huy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cyclingtips.com/2017/04/anna-van-der-breggen-pulls-a-hattrickn-in-fleche-wallonne/|title=Anna van der Breggen pulls a hat trick at Fl\u00e8che Wallonne \u2013 CyclingTips|date=19 April 2017|accessdate=23 April 2017}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/39648741|title=Lizzie Deignan second to Anna van der Breggen in La Fleche Wallonne|date=19 April 2017|accessdate=23 April 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> before emerging triumphant at the first ever [[2017 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge (women's race)|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]] the following Sunday.<ref name=\"LBL2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Liege-Bastogne-Liege_Femmes_2017|title=Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge Femmes|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"LBL2017-2\">{{cite web|last1=Braverman|first1=Jessi|title=Van der Breggen wins the first ever Liege-Bastogne-Liege Femmes|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/liege-bastogne-liege-femmes-2017/results/|website=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> Her dominance in the climbers races earned her the nickname ''Queen of the Ardennes''.<ref name=\"CN Ardennes\">{{cite web|last1=Frattini|first1=Kristen|title=10 riders to watch in the women's Ardennes Classics|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/10-riders-to-watch-in-the-womens-ardennes-classics/|website=Cyclingnews|publisher=Immediate Media Company|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> Three weeks later she won the [[2017 Tour of California (women's race)|Tour of California]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Van der Breggen wins overall in Amgen Women's Race|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/amgen-womens-race-2017/stage-4/results/|website=Cyclingnews|publisher=Immediate Media Company|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> after she surpassed [[Katie Hall (cyclist)|Katie Hall]] during the last stage thanks to bonus seconds won at an intermediate sprint.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Tour-of-California-van-der-Breggen-wins-11145567.php|title=Tour of California: Anna van der Breggen wins women's race|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=Jeffrey M. Johnson, [[Hearst Communications]]|date=14 May 2017|accessdate=24 June 2017|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer, she won the [[2017 Giro d'Italia Femminile|Giro Rosa]] for the second time.<ref name=\"Giro2018\">{{cite web|last1=Braverman|first1=Jessi|title=Anna van der Breggen wins 2017 Giro Rosa|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/giro-ditalia-internazionale-femminile-2017/stage-10/results/|website=Cyclingnews|publisher=Immediate Media Company|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> Her {{ct|DLT|2017}} team had won the opening [[Team time trial]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/giro-ditalia-internazionale-femminile-2017/stage-1/results/|title=Boels Dolmans smash opening TTT of Giro Rosa|first=Jessi|last=Braverman|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|date=30 June 2017|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> and van der Breggen moved into the race lead after placing second in stage 2.<ref name=\"CN2\">{{cite news|title=Van Vleuten claims second stage of Giro Rosa|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/giro-ditalia-internazionale-femminile-2017/stage-2/results/|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|date=1 July 2017|accessdate=1 July 2017|first=Jessi|last=Braverman}}</ref> She won the [[2017 Giro d'Italia Femminile#Stage 10|final general classification]] with more than a minute over [[Elisa Longo Borghini]] and [[Annemiek van Vleuten]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://girorosadotit.files.wordpress.com/2017/04/10a-tappa-cronotabella-1.pdf|title=10^ tappa|language=Italian|trans-title=10th stage|work=[[Giro d'Italia Femminile]]|publisher=[[WordPress]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> After [[Tom Dumoulin]]'s win in the [[2017 Giro d'Italia|men's Giro d'Italia held in May]], it was the first time a Grand Tour was won by both a Dutch man and woman in the same year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Giro-winnares Van der Breggen: een van mijn mooiste overwinningen|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2182352-giro-winnares-van-der-breggen-een-van-mijn-mooiste-overwinningen.html|website=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nLater van der Breggen won a stage and was second overall in the [[2017 Holland Ladies Tour|Holland Ladies Tour]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hollandladiestour.nl/uploads/media/Uitslagen/2017/BLT17_5-Vaals_Results.pdf |title=Boels Ladies Tour |work=UCI |accessdate=18 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904014940/http://hollandladiestour.nl/uploads/media/Uitslagen/2017/BLT17_5-Vaals_Results.pdf |archive-date=4 September 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> which secured her lead in the final standing of the [[2017 UCI Women's World Tour|UCI Women's World Tour]] ahead of van Vleuten.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dataride.uci.ch/iframe/RankingDetails/33?disciplineId=10&groupId=5&momentId=18759&disciplineSeasonId=19&rankingTypeId=1&categoryId=23&raceTypeId=0|title=Women's WorldTour Ranking&nbsp;\u2013 2017: Individual Ranking (Final)|work=[[UCI Women's WorldTour]]|publisher=Infostrada Sports; [[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|date=10 September 2017|accessdate=10 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802003243/https://dataride.uci.ch/iframe/RankingDetails/33?disciplineId=10&groupId=5&momentId=18759&disciplineSeasonId=19&rankingTypeId=1&categoryId=23&raceTypeId=0|archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the [[2017 UCI Road World Championships|Road World Championships in Norway]] her {{ct|DLT|2017}} team finished second to {{ct|TLP|2017}} in the team time trial event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tissottiming.com/File/00030E0105020501FFFFFFFFFFFFFF02|title=Final Results / R\u00e9sultat final: Women's Team Time Trial / Contre-la-montre par \u00e9quipes Femmes|work=Sport Result|publisher=[[Tissot|Tissot Timing]]|date=17 September 2017|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> She also placed second in the [[2017 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's time trial|individual time trial]] behind van Vleuten,<ref name=\"Tissot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tissottiming.com/File/00030E0105020601FFFFFFFFFFFFFF02|title=Final Results / R\u00e9sultat final: Women Elite Individual Time Trial / Contre-la-montre individuel Femmes Elite|work=Sport Result|publisher=[[Tissot|Tissot Timing]]|date=19 September 2017|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> and eighth in the [[2017 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|road race]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/latest-news/chantal-blaak-wins-elite-womens-road-race-352393 |title=Chantal Blaak nets elite women\u2019s road race world title despite crash |accessdate=23 September 2017 |work=Cycling Weekly}}</ref>\n\n===2018: Queen of the Classics===\n[[File:2018 Amstel Gold Race Ladies 214.jpg|thumb|Van der Breggen ''(pictured at the [[2018 Amstel Gold Race (women's race)|Amstel Gold Race]])'' won four [[2018 UCI Women's World Tour|World Tour]] races in the spring of 2018.]]\nAs world number one, she kicked off the 2018 season at the [[2018 Strade Bianche Women|Strade Bianche]]. She won the race, in abysmal weather, after an attack on the penultimate gravel sector of Colle Pinzuto at {{convert|17|km|abbr=off}} from the finish.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kn\u00f6fler|first1=Lukas|title=Anna van der Breggen wins Strade Bianche in heroic solo|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/strade-bianche-women-2018/results/|website=[[Cyclingnews]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> Three weeks later she won the [[2018 Tour of Flanders for Women|Tour of Flanders]] after a {{convert|27|km|adj=on|abbr=off}} solo breakaway. Van der Breggen made her decisive move on the [[Kruisberg]] and increased her lead over the [[Oude Kwaremont]] and [[Paterberg]] to claim her first Tour of Flanders win.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nu.nl/wielrennen/5203022/van-breggen-bekroont-knappe-solo-met-zege-in-ronde-van-vlaanderen.html|title=Van der Breggen bekroont knappe solo met zege in Ronde van Vlaanderen|language=Dutch|date=1 April 2018|accessdate=1 April 2018|work=[[NU.nl]]|publisher=[[Sanoma]]|trans-title=Van der Breggen crowns handsome solo with a win in Ronde van Vlaanderen}}</ref><ref name=\"Flanders2018\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tour-of-flanders-women-2018/results/|title=Van der Breggen storms to Tour of Flanders victory|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|date=1 April 2018|accessdate=1 April 2018|first=Lukas|last=Kn\u00f6fler}}</ref> The following week she won the opening time trial and finished fourth overall in the [[2018 Healthy Ageing Tour|Healthy Ageing Tour]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/healthy-ageing-tour-2018/stage-1/results/|title=Van der Breggen wins Healthy Ageing Tour opener|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|date=4 April 2018|accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hannn.eu/healthy-ageing-tour/en/elite-tour/etappe-5-groningen|title=Stage 5 \u2013 Groningen|work=[[Healthy Ageing Tour]]|publisher=Courage Events|accessdate=5 April 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404235124/https://www.hannn.eu/healthy-ageing-tour/en/elite-tour/etappe-5-groningen|archivedate=4 April 2018}}</ref> before attempting to defend her titles in the Ardennes classics.<ref name=\"CN Ardennes\"/> She finished 38th in the [[2018 Amstel Gold Race (women's race)|Amstel Gold Race]] after an early crash,<ref>{{cite web|title=Wereldkampioene Chantal Blaak wint Amstel Gold Race bij de vrouwen|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20180415_03463299|website=[[Het Nieuwsblad]]|publisher=[[Mediahuis]]|accessdate=15 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref> but won her [[2018 Fl\u00e8che Wallonne (women's race)|fourth consecutive Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]] three days later, on her 28th birthday.<ref name=\"FW2018\">{{cite web|title=Van der Breggen wins La Fleche Wallonne Feminine \u2013 Boels Dolmans rider claims four in a row in Huy|last1=Kn\u00f6fler|first1=Lukas|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/la-fleche-wallonne-feminine-2018/results/|website=[[Cyclingnews]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> She concluded the [[Ardennes classics|Ardennes week]] with her second win in [[2018 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge (women's race)|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]], after she powered away from [[Amanda Spratt]] on the uphill drag to the finish line.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kn\u00f6fler|first1=Lukas|title=Anna van der Breggen solos to Liege-Bastogne-Liege victory|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/liege-bastogne-liege-femmes-2018/results/|website=[[Cyclingnews]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVan der Breggen lives in [[Hasselt, Overijssel|Hasselt]], in the northeast of the [[Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Olympisch Kampioene Anna van der Breggen gehuldigd in Hasselt|url=http://www.rtvoost.nl/nieuws/250875/olympisch-kampioene-anna-van-der-breggen-gehuldigd-in-hasselt#|website=rtvoost.nl|accessdate=17 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref> She comes from a religious family and is a member of the [[Reformed Churches in the Netherlands]].<ref name=\"Onderweg\">{{cite web|last1=van den Bovenkamp|first1=Jasper|title=Anna van der Breggen over topsport en christen zijn|url=https://www.onderwegonline.nl/4378-anna-van-der-breggen-over-topsport-en-christen-zijn|website=onderwegonline.n|accessdate=17 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref> Apart from cycling, she plays the piano and enjoys painting and knitting.<ref name=\"wielerflits1\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;2007\n: 5th Road race, [[2007 UCI Road World Championships|UCI Junior Road World Championships]]\n;2008\n: 8th Road race, [[2008 European Road Championships|UEC European Road Championships]]\n: 10th [[Parel van de Veluwe]]\n;2009\n: 2nd Ronde van Noordhorn\n: 4th Profronde van Surhuisterveen\n: 6th Ronde van De Westereen\n: 8th [[Profronde Stiphout]]\n: 9th Ronde van Heerenveen\n;2010\n: 1st Ronde van Noordeloos\n: 1st Ronde van Oudewater\n: 2nd Ronde van Waddinxveen\n: 5th Gouden Pijl\n: 6th Omloop van Strijen\n: 9th Profronde van Surhuisterveen\n;2011\n: 2nd Ronde van Noordeloos\n: 5th Berkelse Wielerdag\n: 6th [[Profronde Stiphout]]\n: 8th Profronde van Surhuisterveen\n;2012\n: 1st [[File:UEC Champion Jersey.svg|20px]] Time trial, [[European Road Championships|UEC European Road Championships]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Tour de Bretagne]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey green.svg|20px]] Points classification\n::1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] Young rider classification\n::1st Stages 1, 2 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) & 4\n: 1st [[Duo Normand]]\n: 1st Ronde van Noordeloos\n: 2nd Overall [[Trophee d'Or Feminin]]\n::1st Stage 2 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 2nd Omloop van de Ijsseldelta\n: 2nd Wenduine\n: 3rd Ronde van Noordhorn\n: 4th [[GP de Plouay - Bretagne]]\n: 4th Belsele (Sint-Niklaas)\n: 4th Profronde van Surhuisterveen\n: 5th [[Dutch National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Road Championships\n: 5th Overall [[RaboSter Zeeuwsche Eilanden]]\n: 5th Overall [[Tour F\u00e9minin en Limousin]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] Young rider classification\n::1st Stage 2 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 6th [[GP Comune di Cornaredo]]\n: 6th Ronde van Luyksgestel\n: 7th Overall [[BrainWash Ladies Tour]]\n: 9th [[Tour of Flanders for Women|Tour of Flanders]]\n;2013\n: 1st Omloop van de IJsseldelta\n: 2nd Overall [[2013 Troph\u00e9e d'Or F\u00e9minin|Troph\u00e9e d'Or F\u00e9minin]]\n: 2nd Ronde van Zuid Oost-Friesland\n: 2nd RaboRonde Heerlen\n: 3rd [[GP de Plouay]]\n: 4th Overall [[Emakumeen Euskal Bira]]\n: 4th Overall [[Internationale Th\u00fcringen Rundfahrt der Frauen]]\n: [[Open de Su\u00e8de Vargarda]]\n::4th Team time trial\n::5th Road race\n: 4th [[La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne F\u00e9minine|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]]\n: 4th [[Boels Rental Hills Classic]]\n: 4th Profwielerronde Etten-Leur\n: